[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Longitudinal Coordination Reasoning Over Heterogeneous Data, With Human-In-The-Loop Workflow Integration
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Care Coordination Has Resisted Software For Thirty Years
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination, as a clinical workflow, has been a human-mediated problem for almost all of healthcare's history. The reason is structural. Care coordination requires reading across multiple data sources (the EHR, the scheduling system, the prior-authorization status feed, the referral-tracking system, the pharmacy fill data, the home-health agency's status board, the patient's stated preferences and constraints, the patient's caregiver context, the social-determinants assessment), recognizing the connections that matter for this specific patient at this specific moment ("this prior authorization is for the PET scan and the surgical oncologist is going to cancel surgery if the PET scan does not happen by Friday"), generating the next action with the right level of specificity ("call this office, ask for this person, mention this reference number, ask whether the medical-necessity letter from Dr. X has been received"), drafting the communication that the patient or care navigator will use, handing the action to the right human, and following up to confirm closure. The work is intelligent labor; the work also requires institutional knowledge of who at which office handles which kind of request, which payers respond to which kinds of escalation paths, and what the patient's specific constraints are.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Software has, for thirty years, attempted to take pieces of this. The case-management platforms gave care managers a queue and a notepad. The patient portals gave patients access to fragments. The HIE platforms tried to share data across institutions, with mixed success. The bundled-payment-and-value-based-care contracts incentivized institutions to do more coordination, and those institutions hired more care managers. The results were modest. The modal patient with a complex care journey, in 2026, still depends on a heroic care manager (when one is available) or on the patient and their family doing the integration work themselves.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Three things have shifted the workflow shape in the last few years. The first is the maturation of FHIR-native data exchange and the federal interoperability rules that pushed many EHRs to expose patient-data APIs that, while imperfect, are meaningfully better than what existed five years ago. The second is the increasing institutional investment in unified-care-management platforms that consolidate care plans, care-team rosters, prior-authorization status, and referral status in a single workspace, even if each institution's platform is bespoke. The third is the maturation of large language models that can carry on a coherent, sustained conversation while reasoning over the heterogeneous longitudinal data the assistant has access to.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "static rule-based reminders and case-manager workflow tools" to "conversational and proactive assistant that reasons over the consolidated view of the patient's care, surfaces gaps and next actions, drafts the communications, hands actions to humans with structured context, and follows up." The assistant does not have to be a care manager; the assistant has to be the integration layer that humans (the patient, the care manager, the navigator, the office staff) can rely on.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A note on what conversational care-coordination AI is and is not, because the category has been confused. The assistant does not authorize care, does not recommend clinical decisions, does not negotiate with payers on the patient's behalf, does not provide medical advice, does not commit the institution to specific actions. The assistant surfaces, drafts, supports, follows up. The most consequential decisions and authoritative communications flow through licensed clinicians, licensed care managers, and authorized institutional staff. The architectural decisions that follow are about scope discipline, about clarity on what the assistant can and cannot do, and about the human-in-the-loop workflow integration that puts the assistant in the right place in the existing care-management apparatus.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Care Coordination Assistant Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A care-coordination assistant, as designed in this recipe, is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context (the consolidated care plan, active conditions, current medications, allergies, recent encounters, upcoming appointments across all integrated systems, active referrals and their statuses, active prior-authorization requests and their statuses, recent lab and imaging results, the patient's stated preferences, the patient's caregiver context where consented, social-determinants-of-health assessment data where available, transportation and language-and-cultural-context flags), access to a structured library of institutional content (care-pathway templates, condition-specific care-plan-step explanations, referral-process explanations, prior-authorization process explanations, social-services-resource directories, transportation-resource directories, plan-specific benefit and policy information, care-management-team contact information), and a careful set of tools for retrieving from EHRs and care-management platforms, drafting communications, scheduling actions, requesting human handoff, and logging events.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is not one conversation. It is a stream of conversational episodes mixed with proactive interactions, sometimes initiated by the patient (a patient question, a request for help with a specific step), sometimes initiated by the assistant (a proactive nudge based on detected gap or upcoming step), sometimes initiated by the care navigator (the navigator routes a task to the assistant), sometimes initiated by an external event (a prior-authorization denial arrives, a lab result is critical, an appointment is canceled, a transportation booking falls through).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The assistant's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Onboarding and consolidation.** The patient is enrolled in care coordination either by their care team (typical for high-complexity patients) or self-enrolls (typical for moderate-complexity patients with employer-or-payer-driven access). The first conversation does the disclosure work that is central to care-coordination AI: the assistant identifies itself as a chat tool and not a person, states clearly what it can and cannot do (specifically that it is not a care manager, does not authorize care, and does not provide medical advice), names the human-care-management availability, names the care team, and describes the privacy and consent posture in plain language. The patient acknowledges. The assistant then runs an initial consolidation: pulling care-plan, problem-list, medication-list, allergies, encounter-history, scheduled-appointments, active-referral, active-prior-authorization, and recent-lab data from each integrated source, deduplicating and reconciling where sources disagree, and presenting the consolidated view to the patient for confirmation and correction.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Continuous gap detection.** Every change in the consolidated view (a new appointment scheduled, a referral status changed, a prior-authorization decision returned, a lab result available, a medication started or stopped, a missed appointment, an emergency-department visit) triggers a gap-detection pass. The pass identifies missing prerequisites for upcoming care (the surgical pre-op without the cardiology clearance, the chemotherapy without the dental clearance, the PET scan without the prior authorization), missing follow-ups (the abnormal lab result without a follow-up appointment, the new medication without the lab monitoring), missing referrals (the referred specialist who has not been seen and where the referral is timing out), missing social-determinants supports (the chemotherapy patient without the transportation plan, the post-surgical patient without the home-health authorization), and trajectory concerns (the patient who has missed three appointments and may be facing logistical barriers).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-initiated questions within scope.** The patient can engage at any time about within-scope topics: what their next step is, why a step is recommended, what they need to do to prepare for an appointment, what to expect at an appointment, what their referral status is, what their prior-authorization status is, what their out-of-pocket cost is likely to be, what the social-services or transportation resources are, how to reach a specific person on their care team, how to message a clinician with a specific question, how to fill out a specific form, how to get a refill, what to do if they cannot make an appointment. The assistant answers within scope using grounded retrieval; the assistant escalates outside scope (a clinical question, a payer dispute, a complex psychosocial concern, a crisis).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Drafting communications.** The assistant drafts patient-facing and care-team-facing communications: a phone-call talking-point list ("when you call the medical-oncology scheduler, ask for Maria, mention prior-authorization reference number ABC123, ask whether the medical-necessity letter from Dr. X has been received"), a portal message to a clinician, a follow-up email to a referral coordinator, a transportation-booking request, a payer-appeals letter draft (to be reviewed and finalized by a licensed care manager). The assistant does not send communications on the patient's behalf without confirmation; the patient or a human reviews and authorizes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Action handoff to humans.** The assistant routes actions to the right human: the patient (when the patient is the one to take the action), the patient's care navigator (when a navigator is assigned and the action requires institutional access), the patient's primary care physician's office (for clinical follow-up), the prior-authorization team (for payer-side issues), the transportation-services team (for transportation issues), the social-work team (for social-determinants issues), the discharge-planning team (for transitions), the pharmacy (for medication issues). The handoff is structured: the assistant attaches the consolidated context, the specific concern, the relevant data, and the proposed action.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Scheduled engagement and reminders.** The assistant maintains a schedule of proactive engagements: appointment reminders with prep instructions, prior-authorization status checks at intervals, referral-status follow-ups, post-discharge check-ins at twenty-four hours and forty-eight hours and seven days, post-procedure check-ins, medication-start check-ins, lab-monitoring reminders. Reminders are calibrated to the patient's preferences and quiet hours.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Long-term-relationship maintenance.** The assistant maintains conversation history, the consolidated care-plan view across episodes, and stated patient preferences. The assistant references prior context appropriately ("you mentioned last week that the transportation booking for Thursday was an issue; did the social worker reach you about the alternative?") in ways that support continuity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team reporting.** Where the patient has consented to information-sharing, the assistant generates structured summaries (weekly digests for the care navigator, exception-based alerts for the care team) capturing engagement, identified gaps, in-flight actions, and trajectory observations. The assistant's role is not to replace the care team's judgment; it is to give the care team the information they need to be effective at scale.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Off-boarding and tier transitions.** Patients move between care-coordination intensity tiers as their care complexity changes. A patient finishing active cancer treatment may move from high-intensity to maintenance-tier support; a patient newly diagnosed with a complex condition may move into high-intensity. The assistant supports the transition with appropriate communication and care-team coordination.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it the patient's record, prompt it with "you are a helpful care-coordination assistant," and let it engage with users. This breaks in several specific ways, each of which has clinical, operational, and (in some cases) financial consequences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no consolidated view by default.** The patient's data lives in multiple EHRs, multiple scheduling systems, multiple prior-authorization status feeds, multiple referral-tracking systems, multiple care-management platforms. A generalist LLM with access to one EHR will recommend actions that are wrong because it cannot see the appointment scheduled at the second EHR. The consolidation pipeline is the architectural floor; the LLM operates over the consolidated view, not over the fragments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model invents care-plan steps when grounding is weak.** A care-coordination assistant freestyling care-plan steps is generating recommendations the institution has not authored. The care-plan-grounding RAG with strict citation discipline ensures the assistant surfaces steps from the patient's authored care plan and the institutional care-pathway templates, not from its parametric memory.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has weak temporal reasoning.** Care coordination is fundamentally about time and sequence: what happens before what, what depends on what, what is overdue and what is upcoming. Generalist LLMs are inconsistent at this. The temporal-reasoning helpers (date math, timeline construction, dependency-graph computation) are encapsulated in deterministic tools; the LLM uses the tools rather than computing dates in its head.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of multi-system data reconciliation.** The same medication may be listed differently in the oncologist's EHR and the PCP's EHR. The same appointment may appear in two scheduling systems with slight time differences. The patient's address may differ across sources. Reconciliation rules are encoded explicitly; the LLM does not silently pick one version.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of which actions require human review.** Some actions can be drafted by the assistant and authorized by the patient (a portal message, a transportation-booking request). Some actions require licensed care-management review (a payer-appeals letter, a medication-related concern). Some actions require the patient's primary clinician (a clinical question, a care-plan change). The routing rules are explicit; the generalist LLM tries to be helpful and crosses the boundary regularly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has weak prior-authorization workflow knowledge.** Prior-authorization processes are payer-specific, plan-specific, and procedure-specific. The institutional-knowledge layer (which payers respond to which kinds of escalation, what the medical-necessity criteria are for which procedures, which forms are required) is encoded in the institutional content corpus and surfaced via tools; the LLM does not freestyle prior-authorization advice.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has weak transportation and social-services knowledge.** Local transportation-services availability, eligibility rules, scheduling lead times, and accessibility constraints are local-context-dependent. The local-resources directory is encoded in the institutional content corpus.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when not to engage.** Crisis situations, acute clinical issues, complex psychosocial concerns, abuse disclosures, and similar scenarios are outside the assistant's scope and route to the appropriate clinical or social-work resource. The crisis-and-disclosure-screening pipeline is explicit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of consent and information-flow boundaries.** A patient's care-coordination data may include information from multiple institutions with different information-sharing agreements. Some information may be subject to 42 CFR Part 2 (substance-use treatment), state-specific mental-health-privacy provisions, or institution-specific information-sharing rules. The consent and information-flow rules are encoded explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications specific to care coordination.** The assistant operates across institutional boundaries with PHI of the most sensitive variety. The audit, retention, access-control, and information-sharing posture is reviewed by counsel familiar with state-specific care-management and privacy regulations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when the patient needs a human, now.** When the patient is in crisis, when the patient has an acute clinical concern, when the patient is in active escalation, when the patient is failing to navigate, the assistant routes to a human. The escalation pathway is encoded explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Care Coordination Assistant Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.8 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening with continuous emergency screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, longitudinal-context loading, citation grounding, behavior-change-stage tracking, crisis-screening discipline, warm-handoff infrastructure. The care-coordination assistant adds five structural commitments those recipes did not have.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-system data consolidation as architectural primitive.** The patient's care data lives across multiple EHRs, scheduling systems, prior-authorization feeds, referral systems, pharmacy systems, and care-management platforms. The consolidation pipeline pulls from each source, reconciles where sources disagree using deterministic rules, deduplicates, and presents the unified view. The consolidation runs continuously and on demand.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Continuous gap-detection pipeline as architectural primitive.** Every change in the consolidated view triggers gap detection. The detection identifies missing prerequisites, missing follow-ups, missing referrals, missing supports, and trajectory concerns. The detection rules are owned by clinical leadership and the care-management leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Action-routing with named human ownership.** Each action category has a named human owner: the patient, the patient's care navigator, the PCP's office, the prior-authorization team, the social-work team, the discharge-planning team, the pharmacy. The routing rules are explicit, reviewed by care-management leadership, and operationalized with capacity sizing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-institutional information-flow governance.** The assistant operates across institutional boundaries. Information-sharing agreements, consent posture, and information-flow rules are encoded explicitly. Some information categories (substance-use treatment, mental-health, certain other categories) require specific consent for sharing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Human-care-management-team workflow integration as architectural commitment.** The assistant is deployed as part of the existing care-management apparatus, not as a parallel one. The integration with the care-management platform's task queue, the navigator-side review tooling, and the existing escalation pathways is the architectural floor.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle, conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Care-Coordination Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes care coordination specifically harder than the other patient-facing assistant use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The integration surface is the deployment.** The assistant's value is concentrated in the consolidation, gap detection, and action routing across multiple systems. Each integration is a project. Most institutions discover, partway through deployment, that their data-integration story is meaningfully more complex than initially scoped, and the integration work is multi-quarter.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The institutional-knowledge layer is the differentiator.** The assistant's recommendations are only as good as the institutional content corpus: the care-pathway templates, the prior-authorization process documentation, the social-services resource directory, the care-team-contact directory, the plan-specific benefit data. Building and maintaining this corpus is multi-quarter clinical-and-operational work owned by care-management leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The patient-complexity stratification is the operating model.** Different patients need different intensities of coordination. High-complexity patients (newly-diagnosed cancer, multi-comorbidity decompensation, post-discharge transitions, end-of-life) get high-intensity assistant engagement plus dedicated human navigators. Moderate-complexity patients get moderate-intensity engagement with shared navigator capacity. Low-complexity patients get the assistant with on-demand human availability. The stratification is explicit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cultural and linguistic considerations are not optional.** Patients with limited English proficiency, patients from cultures with different family-decision-making norms, patients with low health literacy, and patients with disability-related communication considerations need the assistant adapted accordingly. The multilingual deployment, the reading-level adaptation, and the cultural-fit calibration are architectural commitments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team coordination across institutions is messy.** When the patient's care spans multiple health systems, the assistant may have data from system A but no read access to system B's care plan. The pragmatic answer is patient-as-information-bridge with appropriate trust calibration: the assistant asks the patient to confirm what the other system's care plan says, surfaces the patient's response in the consolidated view with appropriate provenance flagging, and prompts the patient to bring up the other system's information at their next appointment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome attribution is challenging.** A care-coordination intervention's outcomes (reduced readmissions, reduced ED visits, reduced delays-in-care, improved patient experience, improved care-navigator productivity) have many confounders. The outcome demonstration is multi-quarter to multi-year work with careful study design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Liability exposure is meaningful, even though the assistant is not making clinical decisions.** A care-coordination assistant that misses a critical gap (the prior authorization that did not happen and resulted in a delayed diagnosis, the medication interaction that the assistant should have flagged, the abnormal lab without follow-up that the assistant did not catch) can be the proximate cause of harm. The institutional liability counsel reviews the assistant's design, scope discipline, gap-detection sensitivity, and audit posture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-management workforce-displacement concerns are real.** Care managers, nurse navigators, and social workers may reasonably wonder whether the assistant is intended to replace them. The institutional positioning is that the assistant is a tool that lets the human workforce serve more patients with more attentive coordination, not a replacement. The workforce is involved in the design, the training, and the ongoing operation, and the deployment narrative is consistent with the design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Data-quality issues are pervasive.** EHR data, scheduling data, prior-authorization data, and referral data are often incomplete, stale, or inconsistent. The assistant's reasoning has to be robust to imperfect data. The data-quality monitoring and feedback loops are architectural commitments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The patient's family-and-caregiver context is part of the data.** Patients like Marisol have caregivers who are part of the care-coordination story. The assistant's interaction model includes appropriate handling of caregiver communication (with patient consent for caregiver access, with appropriate scope limits, with clear delineation of patient-versus-caregiver communication).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Health-equity considerations are amplified in care coordination.** The patients who most need care coordination are often the patients with the least access to and comfort with digital tools. A care-coordination assistant that reaches the patients who need it least and misses the patients who need it most exacerbates rather than reduces disparities. Per-cohort monitoring is non-negotiable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR-native care-plan, condition, and medication-list APIs are increasingly available.** The U.S. federal interoperability rules pushed many EHRs to expose patient-data APIs, with FHIR R4 as the dominant standard. <!-- TODO: verify; the U.S. ONC and CMS interoperability rules including the Cures Act information-blocking provisions and the Patient Access API mandate have driven broader FHIR API availability since 2021, with the specific scope and quality varying across EHRs --> The CarePlan, Condition, MedicationStatement, AllergyIntolerance, Encounter, ServiceRequest, and Appointment resources are the workhorse for care-coordination consolidation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Unified-care-management platforms have matured.** Several mature commercial care-management platforms (often integrated with EHRs or as standalone offerings) support care-plan authoring, care-team management, task queue management, and patient communication. The assistant integrates with the institution's chosen platform rather than replacing it. <!-- TODO: verify; care-management platforms in 2026 include offerings from Epic, Oracle Health (formerly Cerner), Athena, Salesforce Health Cloud, and several specialty vendors -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle care-coordination reasoning well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from the previous chapter 11 recipes maps to care coordination. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve consolidated data, retrieve institutional content, draft communications, and post tasks for downstream humans.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-EHR data exchange via networks is improving.** TEFCA (the Trusted Exchange Framework and Common Agreement) and the Qualified Health Information Networks are establishing nationwide patient-data exchange, with progress varying by region and use case. <!-- TODO: verify; TEFCA implementation has continued to evolve since the initial Common Agreement in early 2022 with QHINs being designated and onboarded; specific operational maturity varies --> Care-coordination assistants benefit from broader data availability.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature for some segments.** Several mature commercial vendors offer patient-facing care-coordination products at major-payer and major-employer scale. Most major institutions deploying in this space run a hybrid: build a thin-orchestration layer in-house, partner with vendors for specific functions, and integrate with the institution's care-management, EHR, and payer infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Regulatory positioning is generally non-FDA-SaMD for coordination-only assistants.** As long as the assistant does not make therapeutic recommendations or autonomous clinical decisions, it generally does not enter FDA SaMD territory. <!-- TODO: verify; the FDA's Clinical Decision Support Software Final Guidance (2022) and the Cures Act criteria establish the boundary for non-device CDS; specific positioning depends on the assistant's specific recommendations and claims --> The compliance posture is HIPAA-focused with state-specific care-management regulatory considerations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[K
